    {
      "id": 5,
      "topic": "zamowic_accusative",
      "content": "After the verb 'zamówić' (to order), use the accusative."
    },
    {
      "id": 6,
      "topic": "bez_glutenu_bez_laktozy",
      "content": "Useful expressions:",
      "examples": [
        "bez glutenu = without gluten",
        "bezglutenowy = gluten-free",
        "bez laktozy = without lactose",
        "bezlaktozowy = lactose-free"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": 8,
      "topic": "chcialbys_forms_and_cos_do_picia",
      "content": "Use 'chciałbyś' for masculine and 'chciałabyś' for feminine. Memorise the phrase 'coś do picia' (something to drink)."
    },
    {
      "id": 9,
      "topic": "kupic_pic_chciec_accusative",
      "content": "After 'kupić', 'pić', and 'chcieć', use the accusative."
    },
    {
      "id": 11,
      "topic": "napoj_gazowany_literal",
      "content": "'napój gazowany' can be understood literally as 'sparkling/gassed drink'."
    },
    {
      "id": 13,
      "topic": "drink_loanword_and_plaza",
      "content": "In Polish there is also the noun 'drink', but in spoken Polish it refers only to an alcoholic mixed drink. 'Plaża' means beach, and 'na plaży' means on the beach."
    },
    {
      "id": 20,
      "topic": "kuchnia_meaning",
      "content": "'kuchnia' means kitchen. In 'w kuchni' it means in the kitchen. It can also mean cuisine."
    },
    {
      "id": 21,
      "topic": "z_plus_instrumental",
      "content": "After the conjunction/preposition 'z' (with), use the instrumental case."
    },
    {
      "id": 23,
      "topic": "still_vs_sparkling_water",
      "content": "Useful contrast:",
      "examples": [
        "woda gazowana = sparkling water",
        "woda niegazowana = still water"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": 24,
      "topic": "drink_customization_phrases",
      "content": "Useful expressions:",
      "examples": [
        "z lodem = with ice",
        "bez lodu = without ice",
        "z cytryną = with lemon",
        "bez cytryny = without lemon",
        "z cukrem = with sugar",
        "bez cukru = sugar-free / without sugar",
        "z mlekiem = with milk",
        "bez mleka = without milk"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": 25,
      "topic": "coffee_with_milk",
      "content": "Coffee with milk can be called 'kawa z mlekiem' or 'biała kawa'."
    },
    {
      "id": 26,
      "topic": "mrozona_herbata_and_dostac",
      "content": "'mrożona herbata' literally means frozen tea. After the verb 'dostać' (to get), use the accusative."
    },
    {
      "id": 27,
      "topic": "kefir",
      "content": "You can also find kefir in shops and supermarkets across Poland. It is a fermented milk drink."
    },
    {
      "id": 29,
      "topic": "obiad_more_common_than_lunch",
      "content": "'obiad' is much more common in Poland than the English concept 'lunch'. It often refers to the main meal you eat during working hours."
    },
    {
      "id": 30,
      "topic": "double_negation_and_nie_ma",
      "content": "Polish uses double negation. 'There isn't' and 'there aren't' are often translated as 'nie ma'. Also remember 'nie ma nic lepszego' means 'there's nothing better'."
    },
    {
      "id": 31,
      "topic": "dwa_vs_dwie",
      "content": "To translate 'two' into Polish, use 'dwa' with masculine and neuter nouns, and 'dwie' with feminine nouns.",
      "examples": [
        "dwie kawy",
        "dwa soki",
        "dwa piwa"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": 31,
      "topic": "piwo_plural",
      "content": "'piwo' means beer. 'piwa' is the plural form."
    }
  ],
